00:23:32.290 --> 00:23:33.720
Does that help?

00:23:33.720 --> 00:23:35.020
Wonderful.

00:23:35.020 --> 00:23:36.320
Thank you for your
patience with me.

00:23:36.320 --> 00:23:37.990
&gt;&gt; Speaker 9: In your book

00:23:37.990 --> 00:23:41.960
"Resistance" how long did
you spend on the research,

00:23:41.960 --> 00:23:43.950
and how long did it
take you to write it?

00:23:43.950 --> 00:23:45.250
&gt;&gt; Jennifer A Nielsen:

00:23:45.250 --> 00:23:49.540
The research was nearly
a year of research.

00:23:49.540 --> 00:23:51.250
And I was writing
at the same time,

00:23:51.250 --> 00:23:54.310
but it was very intense
focused research,

00:23:54.310 --> 00:23:56.000
and I continued to do it.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:58.870
It was very important to
me to get this story right.

00:23:58.870 --> 00:24:02.490
There are Holocaust
deniers in the world,

00:24:02.490 --> 00:24:03.790
and people who say, "No.

00:24:03.790 --> 00:24:05.090
That never happened."

00:24:05.090 --> 00:24:09.690
And I know if I get a fact
incorrect that somebody can use

00:24:09.690 --> 00:24:12.630
that to say, "Well, if
that fact is incorrect,

00:24:12.630 --> 00:24:15.100
then it's all fiction."

00:24:15.100 --> 00:24:18.500
And so it was very important
to me to get it correct.

00:24:18.500 --> 00:24:21.130
So like when I'm describing
a Warsaw ghetto uprising,

00:24:21.130 --> 00:24:22.430
there's a point where
Chaya [assumed spelling],

00:24:22.430 --> 00:24:26.430
my main character, is
in a building fighting,

00:24:26.430 --> 00:24:29.600
and she thinks this might have
been a furniture store once.

00:24:29.600 --> 00:24:32.740
That building was a
furniture store once.

00:24:32.740 --> 00:24:35.480
Like I get down to that level
of detail because I don't want

00:24:35.480 --> 00:24:39.620
to put something in there
that did not happen.

00:24:39.620 --> 00:24:40.920
&gt;&gt; Speaker 9: And how
long did it take you

00:24:40.920 --> 00:24:42.220
to write it once the --

00:24:42.220 --> 00:24:44.290
&gt;&gt; Jennifer A Nielsen: Writing
it was around six months

00:24:44.290 --> 00:24:47.100
which is about my average
because I'm super obsessive.

00:24:47.100 --> 00:24:48.780
So I just write.

00:24:48.780 --> 00:24:50.920
Thank you very much.

00:24:50.920 --> 00:24:53.890
&gt;&gt; Speaker 10: Where do you get
your inspiration for your books?

00:24:53.890 --> 00:24:55.190
&gt;&gt; Jennifer A Nielsen:

00:24:55.190 --> 00:24:56.630
Inspiration for books
happens this way.

00:24:56.630 --> 00:25:00.510
Okay. Everybody can play this
for inspiration for books.

00:25:00.510 --> 00:25:05.650
So let's say that right
now all the lights go

00:25:05.650 --> 00:25:07.450
out in the whole room.

00:25:07.450 --> 00:25:09.450
And they're out for
exactly three seconds,

00:25:09.450 --> 00:25:14.080
and the end of three seconds
there are only five people

00:25:14.080 --> 00:25:15.650
in this entire room left.

00:25:15.650 --> 00:25:17.600
And you are one of them.

00:25:17.600 --> 00:25:19.180
All right?

00:25:19.180 --> 00:25:23.050
Now where did everybody go?

00:25:23.050 --> 00:25:25.360
Why were you kept?

00:25:25.360 --> 00:25:26.660
Where is everybody?

00:25:26.660 --> 00:25:27.960
Can you find them?

00:25:27.960 --> 00:25:30.530
These sorts of questions
happen to me all the time.

00:25:30.530 --> 00:25:34.390
So everything and everywhere
I am, I just ask questions.

00:25:34.390 --> 00:25:37.840
And then you start
to see story emerge.

00:25:37.840 --> 00:25:41.650
So your goal for today,
before you leave this room,

00:25:41.650 --> 00:25:43.920
I want you to come
up with an answer.

00:25:43.920 --> 00:25:45.460
There's five people left.

00:25:45.460 --> 00:25:47.090
You're one of them.

00:25:47.090 --> 00:25:51.080
Where did they go, and
why were you left here?

00:25:51.080 --> 00:25:52.380
All right?

00:25:52.380 --> 00:25:54.270
You answer that,
you've got a story.

00:25:54.270 --> 00:25:55.940
That's all I do.

00:25:55.940 --> 00:25:57.830
Excellent.

