Information.

00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:04.840
There's two kinds
of ways to research.

00:26:04.840 --> 00:26:06.900
The first is primary sources.

00:26:06.900 --> 00:26:09.900
That's someone who says,
"It happened to me."

00:26:09.900 --> 00:26:12.770
Secondary sources is
a researcher says,

00:26:12.770 --> 00:26:14.640
"This happened to her."

00:26:14.640 --> 00:26:17.070
I'm not a big fan of
secondary resources

00:26:17.070 --> 00:26:19.430
because it passes
through a filter.

00:26:19.430 --> 00:26:21.990
Right? I want to
know as much primary.

00:26:21.990 --> 00:26:26.930
So I will search out
diaries, interviews,

00:26:26.930 --> 00:26:29.760
any first person records.

00:26:29.760 --> 00:26:32.120
Photographs become a
first person source

00:26:32.120 --> 00:26:34.780
because I'm seeing it as it was.

00:26:34.780 --> 00:26:37.920
So my research is always
going to focus first.

00:26:37.920 --> 00:26:41.570
That's why this book
is so valuable

00:26:41.570 --> 00:26:42.960
because it's first person.

00:26:42.960 --> 00:26:46.290
It's her saying,
"This is what we did."

